### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/releated to the feature request?

core

### Description

With Angular 13 it is currently not possible to wrap the `NgModule` to allow for a common pattern, where some of the declarations are exported, and others are internal:

~~~ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';

export function FeatureModule(moduleConfig: FeatureObj) {
  const publicDeclarations = moduleConfig.public ?? [];
  const internalDeclarations = moduleConfig.internal ?? [];
  const exports = moduleConfig.exports ?? [];

  return NgModule({
    ...moduleConfig,
    declarations: [...publicDeclarations, ...internalDeclarations],
    exports: [...publicDeclarations, ...exports],
  });
}

// use it somewhere else:
@FeatureModule({
  imports: [CommonModule],
  public: [SomeComponentToExport],
  internal: [SomeDeclarationOnly]
})
export class MyFeatureModule {}
~~~

This might not be a huge benefit at first glance, but for a library having a whole lot of these kinds of Modules, it would be great to be allowed writing it that way.

In the current version this breaks with the error: `error NG6002: Appears in the NgModule.imports of XguideModule, but could not be resolved to an NgModule class. Is it missing an @NgModule annotation?`

## Testing Modules

The second use case is more like a workaround, but I used it to create TestingModules like this:

~~~ts
// decorators.ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';

export const NgTestingModule = NgModule;

// some-module.ts
@NgModule({ 
   declarations: [SomeComponent],
   providers: [SomeService]
})
export class SomeModule {}

@NgTestingModule({
   // would break when also using NgModule because "SomeComponent appears in more than one module"
  declarations: [SomeComponent],
  providers: [SomeTestingService]
})
export class SomeTestingModule
~~~

Am I missing something or is this approach considered bad practice?

### Proposed solution

Allow Ng* decorators to be wrapped like shown above and do not throw error `error NG6002: Appears in the NgModule.imports of XguideModule, but could not be resolved to an NgModule class.`

### Alternatives considered

Did not find anything else that might work as well.

I tested something like this:

~~~ts
export function featureConfig(moduleConfig: NgModule) {
  return {
     ...moduleConfig,
    declarations: [...publicDeclarations, ...internalDeclarations],
    exports: [...publicDeclarations, ...exports],
  };
}

// some feature module
@NgModule(featureConfig({ /* ... */}))
export class SomeFeatureModule {}
~~~

